headline: Snap Stock Tumbles on Disappointing Earnings Report
summary: Shares of  Snap  were falling sharply Tuesday evening after the social media company reported worse-than-expected second-quarter financial results.  Snap also said daily active users in the quarter increased 9% from last year to 469 million, beating Wall Street estimates of 467.4 million.  “Our rate of topline growth was impacted by a number of factors in Q2,” Snap management said in a letter to investors.

headline: Arista forecasts upbeat third-quarter revenue on strong demand for networking equipment
summary: Demand for the company's ethernet switches and routers, which are widely deployed in data centers, has surged as enterprises accelerate AI-related spending. Arista has projected third-quarter revenue of about $2.25 billion, compared with analysts' estimates of $2.11 billion, according to data compiled by LSEG. Moreover, U.S.-based firms such as Arista are widely expected to benefit the country's tariff policies, as it may help them win new contracts from hyperscale clients and boost market share.

headline: AMD data center results disappoint, shares slump
summary: (Reuters) -Advanced Micro Devices on Tuesday reported disappointing data center revenue, a segment which includes lucrative artificial intelligence chips that investors are betting on for rapid growth.  AMD's shares have climbed more than 40% this year, far outpacing a nearly 12% jump in the benchmark chip index, as investors bet on the company's ability to capitalize on the widespread use of AI.  Chips that power complex AI systems for Microsoft, Meta Platforms, generative AI leader OpenAI and other customers are still feverishly sought after by tech companies.

headline: Chipmaker AMD forecasts third-quarter revenue above estimates
summary: Demand remains robust for AMD's advanced processors that power complex AI systems for Microsoft, Meta Platforms, generative AI leader OpenAI and other customers, with the company set to benefit from cloud giants bumping up their hefty spending plans for building AI infrastructure.  Similarly, Microsoft forecast a record $30 billion in capital spending for the first quarter of the current fiscal year to meet soaring AI demand.  The outlook does not include any revenue from AMD's AI chip MI308's shipments to China as license applications are currently under review by the U.S. Government, the company said.

headline: Snap records slowest revenue growth in over a year amid tough competition for ads
summary: The Snapchat-parent's second-quarter revenue rose 8.1% to $1.34 billion, largely inline with estimates.  The company said it had reverted the ad platform change that unintentionally allowed some ads run at much lower prices, hurting revenue growth in the reported quarter.  Snap said its expanded roll-out of the new ad format — Sponsored Snaps, video ads that appear in user inboxes — across the U.S. and several other global regions is helping by driving more user actions and deeper engagement with ad content.
